               <p>Before Mr. Justice Park.</p>
               <p>895. 
               
                  <persName id="t18300415-229-defend2006" type="defendantName">
                     WILLIAM 
                     GARLAND
                  <interp inst="t18300415-229-defend2006" type="surname" value="GARLAND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-defend2006" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-defend2006" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-defend2006" type="age" value="27"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18300415-229-off1266" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-off1266" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-off1266" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18300415-229-cd1267" type="crimeDate">24th of March</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-229-off1266 t18300415-229-cd1267"></join>, 1 box, value 2s.; 2 coats, value 2l.; 2 pairs of boots, value 1l.; 2 pairs of shoes, value 1s.; 16 neckerchiefs, value 16s.; 2 pairs of trousers, value 15s.; 2 waistcoats, value 8s.; 3 books, value 3s., and 2 sheets, value 5s., the goods of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18300415-229-victim2008" type="victimName">
                           Richard 
                           Kettle
                        <interp inst="t18300415-229-victim2008" type="surname" value="Kettle"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18300415-229-victim2008" type="given" value="Richard"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18300415-229-victim2008" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-229-off1266 t18300415-229-victim2008"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , in the dwelling-house of 
                     <persName id="t18300415-229-person2009">
                        James 
                        Howard
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2009" type="surname" value="Howard"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2009" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2009" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                  
               
                  </rs>.</p>
               <p>RICHARD KETTLE. I am a <rs id="t18300415-229-viclabel1268" type="occupation">servant out of place</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-229-victim2008 t18300415-229-viclabel1268"></join>. On Sunday, the 18th of March, I was at Canterbury, and sent the articles stated in the indictment to town, in a box by a friend - it was to be left at the coach-office in Oxford-road, on the right-hand side from here; this is the direction I put on it (looking at it) - "
               <persName id="t18300415-229-person2010">
                  Richard 
                  Kettle
               <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2010" type="surname" value="Kettle"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2010" type="given" value="Richard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2010" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , Kingston Rectory, near Canterbury;" there was no town direction on it - my friend is not here.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-229-person2011">
                  FRANCES 
                  HOWARD
               <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2011" type="surname" value="HOWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2011" type="given" value="FRANCES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2011" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My father keeps the <placeName id="t18300415-229-crimeloc1269">General Townsend, public-house, near the top of Oxford-road, in the parish of Marylebone; it is between Portman and Quebec-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-229-crimeloc1269" type="placeName" value="General Townsend, public-house, near the top of Oxford-road, in the parish of Marylebone; it is between Portman and Quebec-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-229-crimeloc1269" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-229-off1266 t18300415-229-crimeloc1269"></join> - on the right-hand side going from here- I saw this box under a seat in our house, facing the bar; the person who left it there said it would be quite safe. On Wednesday, the 24th of March, I came down about seven o'clock in the morning - the prisoner was there, standing at the bar with two more men drinking - Young, our man, was minding the bar; I went into another room, and when I came back I saw the prisoner outside the street door, and another man standing outside the door helping him with the box on his shoulder; it was the box I had seen under the seat - I went to the door, and saw him going towards Quebec-street with it; I told the<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183004150106"></xptr>pot-boy to go after him - he was brought back by Lennard, the Policeman; I asked what he took the box away for; he said he did it for a lark - I said it was a fine sort of a lark, and that he meant to thieve it; he used very bad language to me.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Where was the man who minded your bar? A. He had left when the prisoner went out - the box was fitted close under the seat; the prisoner was quite sober - I have seen one of the men, who were drinking with him before; he is a wheelwright.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-229-person2012">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MOORE
               <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2012" type="surname" value="MOORE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2012" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2012" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a shoemaker. I saw the prisoner at the public-house; I knew him before - he was a pot-boy - I called for some purl; the prisoner and another man were sitting in a box facing the bar; they went to the bar, and had some gin - he returned, and pulled this box from under the seat; he said it had come from his friends in the country, and had got ham and bacon in it - he took it out of the door; I saw him go to his lodging, at Mr. Clarke's, the Duke of Cumberland, public-house, Quebec-street, with it; I went in there - he took the box upstairs; the Policeman came in, and took him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Did you know him before? A. Yes - he was very tipsy; I did not see him slip with it.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Do you mean that he was so drunk he did not know what he was about? A. I do not say that- he treated me at the Duke of Clarence, but did not drink himself; he carried the box up stairs himself - Mrs. Clarke said he had had enough gin, and would not let him have any.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300415-229-person2013">
                  MORRIS 
                  LENNARD
               <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2013" type="surname" value="LENNARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2013" type="given" value="MORRIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-person2013" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I went to the public-house, and saw the prisoner there; I told him to bring the box to where he took it from - he went up stairs; I followed him up to the top of the stair-case - he then took the box, flung it down stairs, and told me to take it myself and be d-d; when I went in I saw him at the bar with three men - one of them had a measure of gin in his hand; I asked him where the box was which he had brought from the General 
               <persName id="t18300415-229-person2014">Townsend</persName>
             - he said it was of no consequence to me where it was; after he came down stairs he laid hold of the box and flung it into the street - he went up and down stairs without help; I took him to the General Townsend, and I was obliged to handcuff him there- I found the direction produced, in his pocket.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Did you not ask what he had done with the box he was larking with? A. No - he said he did it for a lark; the box was locked when I found it- he was drunk, but could walk well.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300415-229-verdict1270" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-verdict1270" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-verdict1270" type="verdictSubcategory" value="theftunder100s"></interp>
               GUILTY (of stealing to the value of 99s. only
            </rs>.) Aged 27.</p>
               <p>Recommended to Mercy. - <rs id="t18300415-229-punish1271" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300415-229-punish1271" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-229-defend2006 t18300415-229-punish1271"></join>
               Confined 1 Year
            </rs>.</p>
